data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which both verifies the type and gives a clear failure message instead of an `InvalidCastException`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Your original cast would throw an `InvalidCastException` on the wrong type — which fails the test but with a confusing stack trace rather than a meaningful assertion message. `IsInstanceOfType<T>` gives you a clear "expected `EmailHandler` but got `SmsHandler`" style failure.

If you're on an older MSTest without the generic overload, use:
```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
```
